The `useParams` hook from the `react-router-dom` library returns an object with a string representation of each URL parameter. In your case, the `params` object likely contains a "string | undefined" type for the "id" parameter since it is optional.

To fix the TypeScript error, you can convert the "id" string to an `ObjectId` type using the `ObjectId.createFromHexString` method provided by the `bson` package. Here's how you can modify the `DetailedProductPage` component to fix the issue:

```javascript
import { useParams } from "react-router";
import { DetailedProduct } from "../components/DetailedProduct";
import { useEffect } from "react";
import { ObjectId } from "bson";

export function DetailedProductPage () {
    useEffect(() => {
        document.title = "Товары";
    }, []);

    const params = useParams<{ id: string }>();
    const id = params.id ? ObjectId.createFromHexString(params.id) : null;

    return <DetailedProduct id={id}/>
}
```

In this code, the `useParams` hook is updated to specify that the "id" parameter is of type `string`. Then, the `id` variable is assigned the `ObjectId` representation of the "id" parameter, or `null` if the parameter is undefined.

This should resolve the TypeScript error and allow you to pass the `ObjectId` as the "id" prop to the `DetailedProduct` component.

