```

In this code, the "id" prop is defined as a string in `IDetailedProduct`, and it is passed as a prop to `DetailedProduct` from the `DetailedProductPage` component. In `DetailedProduct`, the `id` prop is used to create an `ObjectId` instance, which is then passed in the request body of the `/api/getProduct` call. After the response is received, the `IProduct` object is stored in the `product` state variable, which can then be used to render the product details.

To check if an ID string is a valid MongoDB ObjectId, you can use the `isValid` method provided by the `bson` package.

Here's how you can validate the ID string in the `DetailedProductPage` component before passing it to `DetailedProduct`:

```javascript
import { useParams } from "react-router";
import { DetailedProduct } from "../components/DetailedProduct";
import { useEffect } from "react";
import { ObjectId } from "bson";

export function DetailedProductPage () {
    useEffect(() => {
        document.title = "Товары";
    }, []);

    const params = useParams<{ id: string }>();
    const id = params.id;

    if (!ObjectId.isValid(id)) {
        // Handle invalid ID here
        return <div>Invalid ID</div>;
    }

    return <DetailedProduct id={new ObjectId(id)}/>
}
```

In this code, the `id` variable is assigned using the same logic as before. Then, the `ObjectId.isValid` method is used to check if the `id` variable is a valid MongoDB ObjectId. If it is invalid, the `DetailedProductPage` component returns a message stating that the ID is invalid.

If the ID is valid, the `ObjectId` constructor is used to convert it to an `ObjectId`, which is then passed as the "id" prop to the `DetailedProduct` component.

